# Product Requirements Document (PRD)
## Enterprise Finance Intelligence Platform (EFIP)

**Document Owner:** Sreeram — Product Owner / Finance Transformation Lead
**Status:** Draft v2.0
**Related:** [Transformation Charter](../docs/00-transformation-charter.md) · [Backlog](backlog.md)

---

## 1. Executive Summary

EFIP is an AI-augmented finance intelligence platform that helps CFOs, Finance Directors, FP&A teams, Controllers, and Supply Chain Finance leaders move from *reporting what happened* to *understanding and acting on why it happened*. It pairs a governed financial data layer with an AI reasoning layer to automate variance analysis, answer natural-language financial questions, and surface forward-looking insight — while preserving the auditability and control finance teams require.

This document defines what is being built, for whom, why it matters, and how success will be measured. It is the product-management backbone of the EFIP Finance Transformation program, sitting between the Transformation Charter (why the program exists) and the Backlog (how it gets executed).

## 2. Vision

> **Give every finance leader a real-time, AI-augmented co-pilot that turns financial data into decisions — not just reports.**

EFIP exists to close the distance between data and judgment. Not by replacing finance professionals' judgment with automation, but by removing the manual labor that currently sits *between* the data and that judgment — so the time finance teams spend is spent deciding, not assembling.

## 3. Mission

To build and prove, as a fully documented transformation program, that an AI reasoning layer — grounded strictly in governed financial data — can materially reduce the time and effort required to explain variance, answer financial questions, and prepare board-ready insight, without compromising the auditability that finance mandates.

## 4. Business Case

**The cost of the status quo:**
- Month-end close cycles of 5–10 days driven by manual reconciliation
- FP&A analysts spend the majority of close-adjacent time explaining variance *after the fact*, rather than modeling forward
- Financial insight is fragmented across ERP, budgeting tools, and spreadsheets with no single governed source of truth
- Forecasts are frequently trend extrapolations rather than driver-based models, reducing their value to leadership

**The opportunity:**
- Automating variance narrative generation directly reduces analyst hours spent on repetitive explanation work
- A natural-language interface over financial data lowers the barrier for non-finance business leaders to self-serve answers, reducing ad hoc requests to FP&A
- A single governed data layer with AI narrative on top improves the speed and consistency of board/executive reporting
- Documenting an auditable AI-grounding approach positions the organization (and the program owner) as a credible practitioner of responsible AI in finance — a differentiator as finance functions face pressure to adopt AI without a governance model

**Why now:** LLM-based reasoning has reached a point where grounded, cited financial narrative generation is achievable without enterprise-scale infrastructure, making this a viable demonstration program even at solo/portfolio scale — while the underlying architecture and governance patterns transfer directly to enterprise deployment.

## 5. Objectives

Mapped to the program-level OKRs in the Transformation Charter, the product-specific objectives are:

1. **Reduce time-to-insight** for variance explanation from manual/reactive to automated/proactive
2. **Prove AI grounding works** — zero fabricated figures across an evaluated set of AI-generated outputs
3. **Deliver role-relevant views** — a CFO/Board view and an FP&A analyst view over the same governed data, each fit for its audience
4. **Establish a reusable governance pattern** — human review sits explicitly in the workflow before AI narrative becomes "final"

## 6. Product Principles

These principles guide every subsequent product decision in this document:

1. **Grounded over generative** — AI explains and narrates real data; it never invents a figure. If the data isn't there, the system says so.
2. **Auditable by default** — every AI output carries a traceable link to its source data.
3. **Human-in-the-loop for anything board-facing** — AI drafts, a human approves before anything reaches an executive view.
4. **One vertical slice before broad shallow coverage** — ship one workflow end-to-end before adding breadth.
5. **Role-appropriate, not one-size-fits-all** — a CFO and an FP&A analyst need different views of the same truth.
6. **Documented decisions, not just documented features** — every non-trivial architectural or product choice is recorded with its rationale (ADRs), not just its outcome.

## 7. Personas

| Persona | Role | Core Need | Primary View |
|---|---|---|---|
| **CFO** | Executive sponsor / consumer | Real-time, trustworthy financial narrative for the board | Executive Dashboard |
| **Finance Director** | Owns transformation outcomes | Faster close, better forecasting accuracy | Executive Dashboard |
