| **Business Leader (non-finance)** | Casual consumer | Plain-language answers, not spreadsheets | NL Query Interface |

## 8. Current Pain Points

| Pain Point | Who Feels It | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| Manual month-end close reconciliation | Controllers, Finance Directors | 5–10 day close cycles |
| Reactive variance analysis | FP&A Analysts | Explanations produced after the fact, under time pressure |
| Fragmented data sources | CFOs, Finance Directors | No single source of truth; reconciliation overhead |
| Trend-line forecasting | CFOs, Supply Chain Finance | Forecasts lack driver-based rigor |
| Insight buried in raw data | Business Leaders | Numbers without narrative; repeated ad hoc requests to FP&A |
| No governed way to use AI in finance | Controllers, CFOs | AI adoption stalls without an auditable grounding model |

## 9. Future State

With EFIP in place:
- Variance is explained automatically, with narrative generated the moment data is flagged — not days later
- Any authorized user can ask a financial question in plain language and get a grounded, cited answer
- The CFO opens a dashboard and sees KPI trends *with* a written narrative explaining the "why," ready for board use
- FP&A analysts spend their time reviewing and refining AI-drafted commentary and running scenarios — not assembling first drafts from scratch
- Every AI-generated statement in the system can be traced back to the source transactions that produced it
- Nothing reaches an executive view without passing through a human review checkpoint

## 10. User Journey

**Example: FP&A Analyst — Monthly Variance Review**

1. Period closes; data lands in the governed data layer
2. System calculates budget-vs-actual variance by cost center and flags variances exceeding threshold
3. Analyst opens the Analyst Workbench, sees flagged variances with AI-drafted narrative attached
4. Analyst reviews each narrative against source data (one click to drill into underlying transactions)
5. Analyst accepts, edits, or rejects each narrative; edits are logged separately from AI-original text
6. Approved narratives flow into the Executive Dashboard, tagged as reviewed
7. CFO opens the dashboard ahead of a board meeting, reads the narrative alongside KPI trends — no manual assembly required

**Example: Business Leader — Ad Hoc Question**

1. Business leader opens the NL Query Interface and asks: *"What drove the increase in COGS in Q2?"*
2. System retrieves grounded data relevant to the query
3. System returns a plain-language answer with citations to the underlying data
4. If the system cannot ground an answer in available data, it says so explicitly rather than guessing

## 11. Product Modules

| Module | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Data Ingestion & Governance Layer** | Ingests GL/budget/forecast data; maintains canonical model and lineage |
| **Variance & Analysis Engine** | Calculates budget-vs-actual variance; applies flagging thresholds |
| **AI Narrative Generator** | Produces grounded, cited variance commentary |
| **Natural-Language Query Interface** | Answers ad hoc financial questions in plain language, grounded in data |
| **Executive Dashboard** | CFO/Board-facing KPI + narrative view |
| **Analyst Workbench** | FP&A-facing drill-down, review, edit, and annotation interface |
| **Audit & Review Layer** | Logs source references, tracks human review/approval state |
| **Forecast Assist (stretch)** | Driver-based forecast suggestions, clearly flagged as AI-assisted estimates |

## 12. Functional Requirements

### 12.1 Data Layer
- FR1: System shall ingest structured financial data (GL, budget, forecast, cost center) from file/sample sources
- FR2: System shall maintain a canonical data model mapping GL accounts to cost centers and budget lines
- FR3: System shall preserve data lineage — every stored figure traceable to its source record

### 12.2 Variance & Analysis
- FR4: System shall calculate budget-vs-actual variance by cost center and period
- FR5: System shall flag variances exceeding a configurable threshold for narrative generation
- FR6: System shall generate AI narrative commentary explaining flagged variances, grounded only in retrieved data

### 12.3 AI / Natural Language
- FR7: System shall accept natural-language questions about financial data and return grounded answers with source citations
- FR8: System shall clearly label AI-generated content as such, distinct from source data
- FR9: System shall reject or flag queries it cannot answer from available grounded data, rather than fabricating a response

### 12.4 Presentation
- FR10: System shall provide an executive dashboard view (summary KPIs + narrative)
- FR11: System shall provide an analyst workbench view (drill-down, editable commentary)
- FR12: Analyst-edited commentary shall be distinguishable from AI-original commentary in the audit trail

### 12.5 Governance
- FR13: All AI outputs shall log the source data references used to generate them
- FR14: System shall support a review/approval step before AI commentary is treated as "final" in the executive view

## 13. Non-Functional Requirements

| Category | Requirement |
|---|---|
| **Auditability** | Every AI-generated statement must be traceable to source data references |
| **Explainability** | AI outputs must state what data and period they're grounded in |
| **Performance** | Dashboard queries return within a few seconds at sample scale |
| **Reliability** | Variance calculations must be deterministic and reproducible from source data |
| **Usability** | Executive view requires no training to read; analyst view assumes finance domain familiarity |
| **Portability** | Runs at local/demo scale; not dependent on a specific enterprise ERP |
| **Documentation** | Every architecturally significant choice recorded as an ADR |

## 14. AI Requirements

- AIR1: All AI-generated financial narrative must be grounded in retrieved source data — no output may state a figure that does not trace to an underlying record
- AIR2: The system must distinguish, in its own output, between what is retrieved fact and what is AI-generated interpretation
- AIR3: When source data is insufficient to answer a query, the system must say so rather than produce a plausible-sounding but ungrounded answer
- AIR4: AI narrative generation must cite the specific data (accounts, cost centers, period) it used
- AIR5: AI-assisted forecasts (stretch scope) must be visually and textually distinguished from actuals and from human-reviewed commentary
- AIR6: Every AI feature must have a documented evaluation approach — a defined rubric or test set used to judge output quality before it's considered "working"
- AIR7: Human review is required before AI-generated commentary is surfaced in the Executive Dashboard (see FR14)

## 15. Security

*(Documented conceptually at this program's scale; full implementation is out of scope for the MVP — see Non-Goals in Section 20.)*

- Role-based access: Executive view, Analyst view, and Admin/config access should be logically separated
- Data-at-rest and data-in-transit protection are assumed requirements for any production deployment, documented as an ADR even where not fully implemented at demo scale
- No production authentication/SSO is built for this program; the architecture should note where it would plug in (e.g., SSO/OIDC integration point) without implementing it
- Audit logs (source-of-truth references, review/approval actions) must be tamper-evident in design intent, even if not enforced at demo scale
- AI query interface must not have the ability to write back to source financial data — read-only by design

## 16. Data Architecture

*(Full detail to be developed in Phase 2 — Enterprise Architecture; summarized here for product context.)*

```
[ Source Data: GL / Budget / Forecast (sample/file-based) ]
                    ↓
       [ Governed Data Layer — canonical model, lineage ]
                    ↓
     [ Variance & Analysis Engine ]  ←→  [ AI Reasoning Layer ]
                    ↓
      [ Audit & Review Layer — logs, approval state ]
                    ↓
   [ Presentation: Executive Dashboard | Analyst Workbench | NL Query ]
```

Key data architecture principles:
- Single canonical model for GL accounts, cost centers, budget and forecast lines
- Every derived figure (variance, AI narrative) retains a reference back to its source records
- AI reasoning layer only reads from the governed layer — never a raw or ungoverned source
- Full reference architecture and technology choices to be finalized and recorded as ADRs in Phase 2

## 17. Reporting

Two primary reporting surfaces, both drawing from the same governed data and audit layer:

- **Executive/Board Reporting** — KPI trends plus AI-generated (human-reviewed) narrative, formatted for board consumption; period-over-period comparison
- **Analyst/Operational Reporting** — full variance detail by cost center, drill-down to transaction level, edit/annotation history

Both surfaces must clearly indicate: reporting period, data as-of date, and review/approval status of any AI-generated content shown.

## 18. KPIs

| KPI | Definition | Target |
|---|---|---|
| Variance narrative accuracy | Rubric-scored: correct, grounded, board-ready | Passes defined quality rubric on sample data |
| NL query grounding rate | % of answered queries with zero fabricated figures | 100% on evaluated query set |
| Time-to-insight | Manual baseline vs. EFIP-assisted, on a comparable example | Directionally faster, documented with a before/after case |
| Review-to-approval time | Time from AI draft to analyst approval | Tracked as a delivery metric once workbench is built |
| End-to-end vertical slice | Demoable data → variance → narrative → dashboard flow | Achieved by MVP (Phase 4) |

