## 20. MVP

The MVP is **one vertical slice**, not partial breadth across all modules:

> Sample GL + budget data → variance calculation → AI-generated narrative commentary (grounded, cited) → Executive Dashboard view, with a basic human review step before the narrative is marked final.

**Non-Goals for this program (not just the MVP):**
- Replacing the ERP or general ledger system of record
- Multi-entity/multi-currency statutory consolidation
- Regulatory filing automation (SOX, IFRS submissions)
- Production-grade multi-tenant security/SSO

Explicitly excluded from MVP scope specifically: natural-language query interface, full analyst workbench editing UI, forecast assist. These are sequenced into v1.1+ once the grounding and narrative approach is proven end-to-end.

## 21. Release Plan

| Release | Scope |
|---|---|
| **MVP (Phase 4)** | Variance vertical slice: data → analysis → AI narrative → dashboard, with basic review step |
| **v1.1 (Phase 5a)** | Natural-language query interface |
| **v1.2 (Phase 5b)** | Full FP&A analyst workbench — drill-down, edit/annotate, audit trail |
| **v1.3 (stretch)** | Driver-based forecast assist |

## 22. Risks

| Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| AI grounding fails on edge cases (ambiguous or missing data) | Define explicit "insufficient data" response behavior (AIR3); test against an evaluation set before calling a feature done |
| Scope creep — this could expand into "build all of finance" | Strict phase gates; MVP vertical slice before any breadth |
| Solo delivery pace variability | Flexible sprint cadence; program designed to pause/resume cleanly between phases |
| Security/governance documented but not fully built could be seen as superficial | Be explicit in all documentation about what is implemented vs. conceptually documented, and why (demo-scale rationale) |
| Sample data may not stress-test AI grounding realistically | Deliberately include messy/ambiguous sample records to test AIR3 behavior, not just clean happy-path data |

## 23. Assumptions

- Sample/synthetic financial data is sufficient to demonstrate the product's value and AI grounding approach; live ERP integration is not required for this program
- A solo builder can credibly run and document each Agile phase (charter, roadmap, architecture, sprints) without a team, using the artifacts themselves as evidence of process
- The audience for the eventual portfolio (interviewers, LinkedIn network) values documented reasoning and governance thinking as much as, or more than, raw feature count
- LLM-based reasoning, appropriately grounded and constrained, is capable of producing finance-appropriate narrative without fine-tuning, for this program's scope

## 24. Dependencies

- Availability of realistic sample/synthetic GL, budget, and forecast data
- Access to an LLM API (or equivalent) capable of grounded, citation-aware generation
- Phase 2 (Enterprise Architecture) must finalize the data model and tech stack before Phase 4 (MVP Build) can begin in earnest
- Phase 3 (Agile Delivery Setup) defines the Definition of Done referenced throughout this PRD's FR/AIR acceptance criteria

## 25. Acceptance Criteria

The MVP (Section 20) is considered accepted when:

- [ ] Sample GL + budget data loads into the governed data layer with preserved lineage (FR1–FR3)
- [ ] Variance is calculated correctly for a known test dataset with expected values verified manually (FR4–FR5)
- [ ] AI-generated narrative is produced for at least 3 distinct flagged-variance scenarios, each citing correct source data (FR6, AIR1, AIR4)
- [ ] At least one deliberately "insufficient data" scenario is tested and correctly triggers a non-fabricated response (AIR3)
- [ ] A human review/approval step exists and must be completed before narrative appears as "final" in the Executive Dashboard (FR14, AIR7)
- [ ] Executive Dashboard renders KPI trend + approved narrative for the test dataset (FR10)
- [ ] Every AI output in the demo can be traced, on request, back to its source data reference (FR13)

## 26. Appendix

- **Related documents:** [Transformation Charter](../docs/00-transformation-charter.md), [Backlog](backlog.md), [Architecture Decision Records](../docs/architecture/adrs/)
- **Glossary:**
  - *Grounded output* — AI-generated content that is derived strictly from retrieved source data, with no fabricated figures
  - *Vertical slice* — a thin, complete implementation of one workflow end-to-end, across all layers, rather than partial coverage of many workflows
  - *WSJF* — Weighted Shortest Job First, a prioritization method (cost of delay ÷ job size) used in the backlog
  - *ADR* — Architecture Decision Record, a short document capturing the context, decision, alternatives, and consequences of a significant technical choice
- **Revision history:**
  - v1.0 — Initial PRD (flat structure)
  - v2.0 — Restructured into 26-section format per program documentation standard